    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/05-posttraining-alignment/02-chat-templates-packing.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: A chat template is a deterministic function that flattens role/content pairs into ONE token stream punctuated by special delimiter tokens (im_start/im_end, header_id/eot_id), and it defines a prompt boundary: everything up to the assistant content is prompt, the assistant content is what the model must generate. Train and inference must produce the byte-identical string.; Train-on-completions-only: the loss mask sets labels=-100 on every prompt/role/user/tool token and supervises ONLY assistant content (plus its stop token). In multi-turn dialogue EVERY assistant turn is supervised, not just the last. Masking removes gradient, not context \u2014 causal attention still lets each assistant token see all prior tokens.; Padding wastes compute: right-padding every short example up to max_length fills most of each row with dead PAD tokens the model still spends FLOPs on. Sequence packing concatenates several variable-length examples into one fixed-length row, driving utilisation from ~1/4 up toward ~90%.; Cross-document attention leakage is the central correctness hazard of packing: with a plain causal mask, the first token of document 2 can attend to the last token of document 1 \u2014 a dependency that never exists at inference. The fix is a block-diagonal causal mask (or Flash-Attention cu_seqlens), which confines attention to within each document, plus per-document position_id resets.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  chattmpl-packing-vs-padding, chattmpl-block-diagonal-attention\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
